Potential Engineering Benefits for Future Validation

The proposed architecture is intended to investigate the potential for:

• Improved modularity and maintainability.

• Simplified subsystem replacement.

• Enhanced diagnostics.

• Predictive maintenance.

• Improved chassis load management.

• Adaptive pitch management during acceleration and braking.

• Improved ride stability through active load control.

• Selective kinetic energy recovery under suitable operating conditions.

• Improved service accessibility.

• Platform flexibility for future vehicle classes.

Performance-related benefits such as improvements in efficiency, range, handling, braking, or grip remain research objectives and require validation through simulation and prototype testing.

